data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

In EF Core 9/.NET 9, the Cosmos DB provider began **throwing `InvalidOperationException` for synchronous LINQ operations** by default, since the Cosmos SDK is inherently async. The `EnableSyncOverAsync()` opt-in was added as a **temporary migration aid**.

**In .NET 11 (EF Core 11), that opt-in is removed.** Your sync calls will throw `InvalidOperationException` regardless of configuration — there is no workaround.

### Every call in your repo is affected:

| Sync (breaks) | Async (replacement) |
|---|---|
| `.ToList()` | `.ToListAsync()` |
| `.First()` | `.FirstAsync()` |
| `.Count()` | `.CountAsync()` |
| `.SaveChanges()` | `.SaveChangesAsync()` |

### Migrated code:

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**
- `Add()` stays synchronous — it's an in-memory tracking call, not I/O.
- All callers up the chain must also become `async`/`await` (this cascades to controllers, services, etc.).
- Remove the `EnableSyncOverAsync()` configuration — it will cause a build error since the API no longer exists.
